Relates to this bug: http://bugs.sun.com/bugdatabase/view_bug.do?bug_id=5079866

Using GMT+0 means Java will parse a custom date format, and if the timezone database does not have a file GMT in $JDK_HOME/jre/lib/zi it will NPE. 

To replicate the problem remove $JDK_HOME/jre/lib/zi/GMT (or rename it to gmt), then run the following: 

{code:java}import java.util.Timezone;

public class Test {

        public static void main(String[] args) {
                try {
                        System.out.println("Trying GMT+0...");
                        TimeZone.getTimeZone("GMT+0");
                }catch(Exception e) {
                        e.printStackTrace();
                }

                System.out.println("Trying GMT...");
                TimeZone GMT = TimeZone.getTimeZone("GMT");
                System.out.println(GMT);
        }
}
{code}

The code in the try catch will NPE, the rest will run fine.

